    {
      "number": 3,
      "id": "I_kwDOHF5N3M5I46FR",
      "title": "Detailed gap analysis",
      "url": "https://github.com/scionfoundation/scion-overview_I-D/issues/3",
      "state": "OPEN",
      "author": "nicorusti",
      "authorAssociation": "COLLABORATOR",
      "assignees": [],
      "labels": [],
      "body": "We decided to omit a detailed gap analysis in the initial overview. We had a list of current Internet issues in [this commit](https://github.com/scionfoundation/scion-overview_I-D/commit/8259808cbbd41e8c1d8e39eb7ffc63b8d516433c) that we then removed. This list  could be handy for a more detailed gap analysis (perhaps in a dedicated draft).\r\nI'm opening this so that we keep this in mind  \r\n\r\n\r\n ",
      "createdAt": "2022-05-02T13:17:06Z",
      "updatedAt": "2022-05-02T13:17:06Z",
      "closedAt": null,
      "comments": []
    }
  ],
  "pulls": [
    {
      "number": 1,
      "id": "PR_kwDOHF5N3M42rrtN",
      "title": "Initial review",
      "url": "https://github.com/scionfoundation/scion-overview_I-D/pull/1",
      "state": "MERGED",
      "author": "nicorusti",
      "authorAssociation": "COLLABORATOR",
      "assignees": [],
      "labels": [],
      "body": "I went through the draft, some general feedback: \r\n\r\n- Introduction: perhaps we can  create a  new short introduction paragraph, where we briefly discuss the problem and our solution. I guess we can move the more detailed  problem statement in a separate paragraph\r\n-  Lots of the challenges with today's routing are described quite well in this draft: https://www.ietf.org/archive/id/draft-king-irtf-challenges-in-routing-07.html \r\n- When we describe drawbacks, I'm not sure if we also want to mention why attepmts to fix the existing are not enough (i.e. routing with colours, SR, ...)\r\n- Do we want to move the motivation/gap analysis into a different draft?\r\n- Lots of people will ask themselves: what do I need to deploy this. I can eventually help with the deployment section\r\n- I noticed that a lot of times we use \"we\". I see that some IETF drafts also use it, but not so often. I feel that using it a lot creates a bit of a \"divide\" between what our vision is, and what others might perceive... I think this is good when writing a paper/book (because authors want to stress that they are presenting their vision), but perhaps a more neutral language is more appropriate here, as our goal is to get consensus and to have our solution as widely accepted as possible. Not something super important, but had these thoughts in mind.  ",
      "createdAt": "2022-04-24T11:50:52Z",
      "updatedAt": "2022-04-26T12:08:16Z",
      "baseRepository": "scionfoundation/scion-overview_I-D",
